definition.value: A methylbenzyl alcohol that is toluene in which one of the ortho hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxymethyl group.

A trihydroxyflavanone in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at positions 3', 4' and 7. It is found in Acacia mearnsii, Vernonia anthelmintica and Dalbergia odorifera and has a protective affect against oxidative stress-induced mitochondrial dysfunction.

A spirostanyl glycoside that is digitogenin in which the 3-hydroxy group is substituted by a beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->2)-[beta-D-xylopyranosyl-(1->3)]-beta-D-glucopyranosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactopyranosyl group. It is a steroidal saponin isolated from the foxglove plant, Digitalis purpurea. It is used extensively as a mild non-ionic detergent for extracting proteins from membranes for structure and function studies.
The D-enantiomer of isoleucine.
A glycotriaosylceramide having N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the triaosyl component.
A trimethylxanthine in which the three methyl groups are located at positions 1, 3, and 7. A purine alkaloid that occurs naturally in tea and coffee.
A cyclic carotene obtained by the cyclisation of lycopene.
Any hydroxyflavone with a hydroxy substituent at position 3'.

A C19-gibberellin that is a pentacyclic diterpenoid responsible for promoting growth and development. Initially identified in Gibberella fujikuroi, it differs from gibberellin A1 in lacking an OH group at C-2 (gibbane numbering).

A phosphonic acid resulting from the formal oxidative coupling of the methyl group of methylphosphonic acid with the amino group of glycine. It is one of the most commonly used herbicides worldwide, and the only one to target the enzyme 5-enolpyruvyl-3-shikimate phosphate synthase (EPSPS).
An L-lysine derivative that is the L-enantiomer of homoarginine.
A pyridine nucleoside consisting of nicotinic acid with a beta-D-ribofuranosyl moiety at the 1-position.
A dipeptide consisting of beta-alanine and L-lysine units joined by a peptide linkage.
The acetate ester formed between acetic acid and ethanol.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of methacrylic acid.
A monochlorobiphenyl carrying a chloro substituent at position 4.
A benzene ring substituted with a sulphonic acid group at position C-1, and hydroxy groups at C-3 and C-4.
An optically active form of selenocystathionine in which both amino acid residues have L-configuration.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-hydroxy-3-methyl-2-oxopentanoate.
A dimethoxyflavone that is the 3,7-di-O-methyl derivative of quercetagetin.
A monohydroxyacetophenone that is acetophenone substituted by methoxy groups at positions 2' and 6' and a hydroxy group at position 4'.
A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of nonanoic acid.
A chlorocatechol that is catechol substituted by a chloro group at position 4.
A 3-enoyl-CoA in which the beta C=C double bond has cis stereochemistry.
A vetispirane sesquiterpenoid that consists of (2R,5S,6S,8S,10R)-8-hydroxy-10-methyl-2-(prop-1-en-2-yl)spiro[4.5]decane bearing a formyl substituent at position 6.
A diadenosyl triphosphate having the two 5'-adenosyl residues attached at the P(1)- and P(3)-positions.
